<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="349" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[175,1005,595,1414]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,312,1286,1307]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Discussion.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Champion" box="[324,505,1286,1307]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" pagination="1 - 130" refId="ref6683" refString="Champion, G. C. 1906. Curculionidae, Curculioninae, Zygopina. In: Biologia Centrali- Americana, Insecta, Coleoptera, IV, 5: 1 - 130." type="journal article" year="1906">Champion (1906)</bibRefCitation>
noted the similarity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1906" box="[787,931,1286,1307]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lechriops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblongulus">
<emphasis box="[787,931,1286,1307]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">L. oblongulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1876" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Piazurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">L. californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1906" box="[305,516,1313,1334]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lechriops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblongulus">
<emphasis box="[305,516,1313,1334]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Lechriops oblongulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very uniformly colored above, other than the sutural spot on the elytra. Males of the two species differ conspicuously in secondary sexual charactreristics and in genitalia. 
<collectingRegion box="[556,632,1366,1387]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Arizona</collectingRegion>
populations possess narrow sublateral lines of white setae on pronotum, whereas those in 
<collectingRegion box="[678,761,1393,1414]" country="Mexico" name="Durango" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Durango</collectingRegion>
lack them.
</paragraph>
